# Case Study: How Annual Members and Casual Riders Use Cyclistic Bikes Differently

**Author:** Hoang Do Phan  
**Date:** 2026-05-19

---

## Background

This project is part of the [Google Data Analytics Professional Certificate](https://www.coursera.org/professional-certificates/google-data-analytics) program.

Cyclistic is a fictional bike-share company based in Chicago that operates more than 5,800 bicycles and over 600 docking stations. The company offers different types of bicycles including traditional bikes, reclining bikes, hand tricycles, and cargo bikes to make the service more accessible for different riders.

Customers who purchase single-ride or full-day passes are considered **casual riders**, while customers who purchase yearly subscriptions are classified as **annual members**.

Cyclistic’s finance team has determined that annual members are significantly more profitable than casual riders. Because of this, the marketing department wants to better understand customer riding behavior in order to develop effective strategies that encourage casual riders to purchase annual memberships.

The marketing analytics team is interested in analyzing historical trip data to identify riding patterns, customer behaviors, and trends between both rider groups.

